er so slightly when he was in the act of unfolding something. Krug — for it was he — showed her the blurred paper. He was a huge tired man with a stoop.

'But it might not help,' she whined, 'a stray bullet might hit you.'

(You see the good woman thought that bullets were still flukhtung about in the night, meteoric remnants of the firing that had long ceased.)

'I am not interested in politics,' he said. 'And I have only the river to cross. A friend of mine will come to fix things tomorrow